    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Describe your issue\n\nMainly affects memoryview code.\r\n\r\nhttps://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc-4.7.0/gcc/_005f_005fatomic-Builtins.html The advantage is that these represent the C11/C++11 memory-model much better while the `__sync` ones don't really correspond to a memory model. So it'd let us match more closely with the implementations using the C/C++ standard library.\r\n\r\nPerformance-wise this mostly matters on non-x86 platforms (I believe).\r\n\r\nThe disadvantage is that it requires gcc-4.7 (2012) instead of 4.4 (2009). We do have fallback (locked) code though. I don't think this version bump is hugely restrictive but posting here to gather objections.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately MSVC is (predictably) as mess, and doesn't have an sensible upgrade from what we have.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "The GCC minimum version bump looks completely harmless, no one is using GCC versions that old anymore. We do regular conservative bumps in NumPy, and are at >=9.3.0 now - I can't remember any recent complaint, it's been years since the last one when we bumped from 6.x to 8.x.\n\nHowever, I think the real thing to worry about is whether this introduces a new requirements to link against `libatomic` on 32-bit and maybe also some other niche platforms. `__sync` functions usually don't require that, but `__atomic` ones do more often. If that's the case for regular usage of memoryviews, that is likely to be a blocker here. You don't want every user to have to do this kind of thing in their build config:\n\nhttps://github.com/scipy/scipy/blob/3afcc475b1d5003bf95e283a7afeb04d094aa6e4/scipy/meson.build#L672-L709",
